<tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 794<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/10/03 12:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=448.topic&index=281>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Morality is not relative.&quot;</span><hr size=1> You guys keep coming back to that.<br>
<br>
Simply because something is debatable does not mean that there is no single best or correct judgement.  We may not possess all of the tools or information necessary to make that judgement or have that knowledge, but that does not mean that the final judgement and/or knowledge does not exist!  We do the best with what we are given.  Yes, there is always the possibility that we lack further evidence or knowledge of the Truth, but that doesn't mean that we should resign ourselves to remaining ignorant of it!  We take what we have, what we know, and we do our best with it.  Of course there is the possibility that we are wrong, that there is further evidence, etc.  That is why we are not to judge others.  That is also a core principle.  Now you will say, of course, &quot;But we are judging Saddam!!&quot;  Remember way back in the thread...?  If someone's moral values clash with mine, but they do not infringe on the safety or the rights of others, that's just dandy.  Now - wouldn't it be safe to say that Al Qaeda infringed on a whole hell of a lot of Americans' rights and safety?  As for Saddam, the whole argument of his threat to us is ongoing, but for those who believe he does the same, the justification is present.  Even if he hasn't infringed on ours, of course, he sure as hell infringes on those of Iraqis.  Maybe that's why some of the biggest supporters of this war are Iraqis.  Their rights and safety have been made a joke of by Saddam.  It's called &quot;just war&quot;...<br>
<br>
&quot;The question is whether it's a choice or a natural urge that they were born with. Whichever you believe it to be will determine your decision&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm not really sure, not being a homosexual myself.  I'll give homosexuals the benefit of the doubt and say its probably a mix of both, though.  We're each drawn to particular sins, some more than others.  In each case, it is that person's responsibility to exert self discipline.  I'll say it again - homosexuality is just another sin.  If I singled out homosexuals for judgement I'd have to single out everyone else on the planet, myself included, for the various other sins we've all committed.  My only peeve with homosexuals is when they decide that they're going to flaunt their perversion publically, especially for the purpose of attempting to numb society into accepting homosexuality as a norm.<br>
<br>
Walkabout, I don't really have much to say except that I sure am glad I don't live in your fairy tale world.  Church bells?  You just showed much better than I the ridiculousness of moral relativism, probably without even knowing it.  Of course, you think it was a perfectly valid point... more's the pity.<br>
<br>
Myself, I'm glad that Bush wants to liberate Iraq from a murderous dictator.  I'm glad that he realizes that yes, Western values of individual liberties and civil rights are &quot;better&quot; than despotic tyranny.  I'm glad he realizes that changing Middle Eastern political culture is the one and only way to solve the problem of terrorism.<br>
<br>
You probably suscribe to a &quot;passive realist&quot; viewpoint:  Take the world as you find it. You can't change people. Assume the worst. Earth is a dark and dreary place and you pocket your winnings where and when you can. Don't ever bet big on optimistic scenarios. We live in an oasis, let &quot;them&quot; kill each other. Applied to the Arab and Muslim world, this outlook says &quot;they&quot; can't change. The best you can hope to do is manage the problem, but don't be a fool; don't try to solve it. Don't stick your neck out; *you* can't and shouldn't really do anything. Better to work with reliable thugs (Saddam) than with unpredictable idealists (Bush). Bribe bullies to leave you alone. Israel's real crime, for example, is that makes trouble for us. After all, the people who hate Israel don't mind dead Arabs or occupied countries. They don't care if Syria occupies Lebanon. They don't care if Saddam kills Iraqis. Israel is an inconvenience to the Westerners who want to go along and get along, because suicide bombing and war are just what &quot;those&quot; people do, and Westerners should know better.<br>
<br>
Am I right?  Go ahead... that's not the world that I live in.  And if that's the way most Europeans think, then I'm proud for America to stand against them.  The acid test will be, as with the rest of it, after Iraq is over with... I guess we'll see then who's right. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.visveres.myguilds.com/sigs/caledhon.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A> at: 3/10/03 12:17:31 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=walkabout>Walkabout</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 274<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/10/03 12:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=448.topic&index=282>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Morality is not relative.&quot;</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Myself, I'm glad that Bush wants to liberate Iraq from a murderous dictator. I'm glad that he realizes that yes, Western values of individual liberties and civil rights are &quot;better&quot; than despotic tyranny.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
