Just because you are ignorant of something, does not mean that it is not the case. The fact that you do not possess a particular piece of knowledge does not of necessity invalidate the truth of that knowledge!!<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That is correct, it doesn't invalidate the fact that there could *potentially* be some type of absolute moral code somewhere should there be a deity that cares enough to have one.  However, it DOES invalidate our interpretations of said absolute moral code as relative to what YOU believe.  Why is that so hard for you to grasp?  Yes, there MIGHT be an absolute moral code, but without the communication of it, our interpretations of morality ARE RELATIVE.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Can one set of moral values be objectively better than another? <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
We would all say that our morality code was &quot;better&quot; than someone else's.  We would find anything we possibly could to justify ours as &quot;better&quot;.  Just look at Walkabout's attempts to justify his belief that spanking children is immoral... and our's to justify our belief that it is not.  Which is correct?  No one knows, therefore it's relative to what YOU believe.<br>
<br>
I don't believe that lust nor envy are sins.  Acting upon those emotions could be sins, but having them are not.  Having sex in the manner that gays were created is a sin.  Gay people have lust, they have envy, they have all of our genetic makeup and additionally, they can't have sex?  <br>
