<br>
Caledhon,......I can't agree more with that post.  <br>
<br>
The concept of original sin is not necessarily being screwed, but more we have a choice.  The tree of knowledge an allegory for if I do not know better than to sin and I sin, does that then mean it is a sin.  Adam and Lillith were happy in their ignorance of the outside world.  Adam had God cast Lillith out because she didn't subjegate to his will.  <br>
<br>
Does that mean that Adam sinned, or does that mean Lillith sinned, they weren't aware of sin, had no concept of the knowledge of equal rights, morality, and such.  <br>
<br>
Adam and Eve were happy until the shinning one showed them the knowledge, and suddenly they were aware of their nakedness, Eve had her guilt, Adam had his, and now humanity has theirs.<br>
<br>
These allegories are told to illustrate a base in humanities sense of self.  They are as base as &quot;I don't let my children watch TV because TV is violent&quot;, yet that child will enter the world and see violence none the less.  Our job as a parent is to educate, and know that in educating we take the chance of stearing down the wrong path.<br>
<br>
It is a choice, once educated, aware, that we have a fundemental choice between being good, and being evil and choosing good; then and only then are we even on the path to entrance to heaven.<br>
<br>
That is why morality is relative, because morality is personal.  Despite the society I am in, I choose to do what I believe is right.  To have the moral conviction to fullfil what your personal edicts dictate. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.visveres.myguilds.com"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.visveres.myguilds.com/sigs/thiaz.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
